children.value: Sir Archibald Blake urgently requests your help.

children.name: Text
children.value: Dear friend, what you read in the news is trueâ€” Her Majesty is gone! My one consolation is that it seems by choice, for she left this parting note: "Don't fret, Archie dear. I'm off South to restore our imperial gloryâ€” will return when that's done". Please, can I trust you to ensure her safe return? I must remain here, to allay the chaos in her absence.

children.name: Text
children.value: Where has the Queen gone!? Worried sick and left to deal with a headless state, Sir Archibald Blake has come to you for help. You are his only hope in finding Her Majesty and convincing her to return to her royal duties. Organise an expedition South to go after her.

children.value: We are lucky there is even a faint possibility of returning this journal to a semblance of its original condition. We must first see to the binding: people tell me a flour-based glue will be gentler on such a delicate manuscript than an acid one, and that we'll also want the precision and punch of modern sewing machines for the stitching.

children.name: Text
children.value: HMS AJAX â€” Captain Richardson's Log

children.name: Text
children.value:
Following the Kingâ€™s commands to intercept Admiral Silvaâ€™s flotilla, we have arrived at Cape Trelawney at 1pm.
La Coronaâ€™s entire armada are hereâ€” their flagship especially, being of imposing size and might. Such a disproportionate escort suggests that our informants were correct: they must be transporting the Sceptre of Capon our King seeks.

children.name: Text
children.value: La Coronaâ€™s fleet is vast in size and number, but ours staffed with seamen both seasoned and loyal. We have a chance of winning a decisive victory against the enemy here at Trelawney â€” but not if we fixate on recovering the sceptre, as the King is insisting... I admit, taking the talisman would greatly damage La Corona's national spirit, but what of our own?â€” when a thousand or more sailors are sent to their deaths for a trinket! No, we must have no other thought than employing the best tactics to win the day.

children.name: Text
children.value:
Since the King will not now leave the safety of the fortress atop the cliffs, we may be able to blame the fog for not complying with his signals.
There were other incidents today. At 3pm we intercepted two enemy gunboats, and ran them aground between two small islands to the Southeast, with cliffs like two guard dogs facing one another.
At 4:30pm we discovered a frigate bearing the emblem of La Corona smuggling crates from a pirate cove amid the spiral-shaped cluster of islands that lie due east.
Lastly, we had a skirmish with a ship-of-the-line near an old watchtower between the three large islands due west. She sank with all her cargo.

children.name: Text
children.value:
La Corona opened fire this morning. We engaged in battle at 10am, southeast of the region, and it lasted until seven in the evening.
We lost many good men todayâ€” the sly young Admiral Silva having deployed mines to protect the enemy convoy. It was the King's command that we attack in a single line, parallel to the enemy formation. Fortunately, I was able to persuade the fleet to ignore this instruction, and instead arrange themselves in two perpendicular columns to cut the enemy line, and as a corollary, avoid the mines. Still our lead ships were blown open, but it left a path clear for the rest of us. The enemy fleet, being snipped into thirds, were vulnerable to broadsides. We proceeded to drive them toward their own mines, and though in the mayhem there were casualties on both sides, we knew victory for the Empire had been won.
We thank those brave sailors who lost their lives today that we ourselves survived, and shall never forget their sacrifice. The price would have been far greater had we sworn blind obedience to the King's strategy.

children.name: Text
children.value:
It will doubtless anger him to hear his orders were defied, but I stand by my decision. It may even please him to hear I have been wounded for my arrogance. It is likely my dress and decorations made me a conspicuous target, and I took musketfire to one side.
My arm still has full functionâ€” and my head is not half as foggy as the doctor thinks it might beâ€” so I will continue to command until our operation here is concluded. La Corona may have suffered a defeat of magnitude today, but their flagshipâ€” the gargantuan SantÃ­ssima VitÃ³riaâ€” managed to escape unscathed.

children.name: Text
children.value:
The King is indeed mad. He appears to care nothing for our victory, and was upset in the extreme to learn that we hadn't yet begun pursuit of the SantÃ­ssima VitÃ³ria, for he is adamant that the Sceptre of Capon is aboard.
Having received word that the flagship was heading northeast, His Majesty ordered our Captain Richardson â€” of the HMS Ajax â€” to go after her. Under no circumstances will he permit us to accompany them. I have tried to inform the King that the Ajax is ill-equipped for the duel, but my injury leaves me weak, and I have had to retire to my quarters. SantÃ­ssima VitÃ³ria may be the largest man-of-war ever built. Richardson knows he leads his men to their deaths, but he has always been a man unswerving in his sense of duty.

children.name: Text
children.value:
It is unseasonably, morbidly hot. A rowboat was found this morning, beached on the headlandâ€” brought on the current presumably, for its occupants are three days dead of thirst. In a clenched hand, a letter from Richardson; these men he sent to find help; the crew of the Ajax surviving a clash with the SantÃ­ssima VitÃ³ria only by swimming to an island southeast of the headland.
We immediately dispatch a rescue boat, but it is too late: Richardson and his crew have met the same fate. We find no trace of the SantÃ­ssima VitÃ³ria either. His Majesty's reaction is predictable. These lives are on his hands, yet he weeps only for the sceptre.
My wounds fester, and my fever worsens. The doctor says I must put down my pen.

children.name: Text
children.value: In the best interest of both our nations, I, Vasco Oliveira Silva, servant of His Majesty King JoÃ£o of A Coroa, compromise to surrender the piece of the Sceptre of Capon currently in my custody, namely the pommel of the Sceptre, in the event of my failing to discover the final piece of the Sceptre (the eagle) first, so long as the counterparty agrees to do the same in the opposite event.

children.name: Text
children.value: 2am: Our patrol was uneventful. The night is calm. Thanks to Admiral Nadaskyâ€™s exceptional strategy, the HMS Ajax and many of her sister ships have prevailed in the battle of Trelawney.

children.name: Text
children.value: 9am: We have new orders. The Ajax has been chosen by His Majesty himself to chase and board the SantÃ­ssima VitÃ³ria, where we are to retrieve an object of great importance. The enemy have a significant advantage, but after all the HMS Ajax is a logical choice, being one of the few frigates still in good condition. I must have faith we can achieve our goal, or my men will not.

children.name: Text
children.value: 12pm: Encountered the SantÃ­ssima VitÃ³ria Southeast of the mainland, she opened fire on sight. I commanded the Ajax to retaliate. Disabled their rudder, and saw enemy flagship wreck against the east coast of the mainland, pulled in by strong current. Sceptre gone with her. We too are filling with water.

children.name: Text
children.value:
HMS Ajax sunk. One rowboat, myself and the rest swimming for shore. A desolate island, no fresh water. Heat unbearable. Currents too strong to attempt a crossing, sending rowboat to get help.

October 19th,
No word from the rowboat. We will die here...

October 21st,
Hope gone. Our King has forsaken us.

children.value: The Queen is ready to lay the foundations of a new city at Crown Falls.

children.value: The Queen has entrusted you with building a new Imperial Capital at Crown Falls, a beautiful land that extends as far as the eye can see. But every great metropolis must begin as a humble village.

children.name: Text
children.value: The Queen spurs you to expand your settlement on Crown Falls.

children.name: Text
children.value: Your settlement at Crown Falls is promising, but it's as yet very far from the grand metropolis the Queen saw in her sleep. It is time for it to grow into a town.

children.name: Text
children.value:
Reach City Status: Town
[Conditions QuestCondition CurrentAmount]/[Conditions QuestCondition Amount] [AssetData([Conditions QuestCondition Context]) Text]

children.name: Text
children.value: The Queen stresses the importance of establishing a city at Crown Falls.

children.name: Text
children.value: Not only is Crown Falls a pleasant land, that is of historical and emotional significance to her people, but the Queen has long-term strategic and commercial motives for establishing a city here.

children.name: Text
children.value:
Reach City Status: City
[Conditions QuestCondition CurrentAmount]/[Conditions QuestCondition Amount] [AssetData([Conditions QuestCondition Context]) Text]

children.name: Text
children.value: The Queen is looking forward to having a capital at Crown Falls.

children.name: Text
children.value: Your city is almost there! It still has some growing to do, but soon enough, it will be granted the status of Capital of the region. Of course, the Queen will not be satisfied until it is considered a Capital of the Empire, but solid progress nonetheless!

children.name: Text
children.value:
Reach City Status: Capital
[Conditions QuestCondition CurrentAmount]/[Conditions QuestCondition Amount] [AssetData([Conditions QuestCondition Context]) Text]

children.name: Text
children.value: The Queen longs to see the Metropolis of her dreams.

children.name: Text
children.value: The Queen had a very clear vision from the moment she set eyes on Crown Falls: a vast metropolis, the most beautiful and advanced in the whole of her Empire â€”nay, in the World. That dream is closer to reality than ever before.

children.name: Text
children.value:
Reach City Status: Metropolis
[Conditions QuestCondition CurrentAmount]/[Conditions QuestCondition Amount] [AssetData([Conditions QuestCondition Context]) Text]

children.name: Text
children.value: The Queen revels in the Metropolis you have built.

children.name: Text
children.value: To reach the next city status, you must attract a certain number of residents. Build enough residences for them and make sure at least their basic needs are fulfilled.

children.name: Text
children.value: "By the Grace of God", such is the epithet that has accompanied my name ever since I was anointed as Queen. My capital too must be blessed.

children.name: Text
children.value: The Queen runs no secular state: if this city is to become an imperial capital, she needs a church to remind her people it was an almighty God who chose her for the throne.

children.name: Text
children.value: The Queen wants you to build a church.

children.name: Text
children.value: Do you think I only fancy a big city here out of whim? Crown Falls is an incredibly advantageous joint for our trade routes. I want to see the largest commercial hub on the whole of The Old World!

children.name: Text
children.value: Standing at the southernmost tip of the Old World, Crown Falls is the perfect location for a commercial port to connect to the wider world. The Queen therefore insists on your improvement of the city's harbour area.

children.name: Text
children.value: The Queen wants you to enlarge your harbour area.

children.name: Text
children.value: I won't be content with a cold-hearted industrial city. I want a metropolis that brims with the most avant-garde minds of the century â€” poets, artists, entertainers, intellectuals...! I want it teeming with interesting visitors!

children.name: Text
children.value: The Queen is set on turning Crown Falls into a landmark of culture, a place to attract distinguished visitors from far and wide. Though they say culture is priceless, tourists tend to be quite lucrative too.

children.name: Text
children.value: The Queen wants you to promote culture.

children.name: Text
children.value: My metropolis has to be the spearhead of the era, I want it the most technologically advanced city on Earth. I won't rest until every street dazzles with electrical lights!

children.name: Text
children.value: Since Her Majesty is resolved to show she is a modern Queen, and that Crown Falls is the spearpoint of imperial progress, there seems no better way to do this than with flashy displays of electricity.

children.name: Text
children.value: The Queen wants you to light up the streets of Crown Falls.

children.name: Text
children.value: The Queen envisions a World's Fair at Crown Falls.

children.name: Text
children.value: Your city on Crown Falls is almost unparalleled! The one thing that could elevate it further would be to hold the greatest World's Fair ever seen.

children.name: Text
children.value: The Queen is exultant to see the World's Fair at Crown Falls.

children.name: Text
children.value: The Queen is happy to see the World's Fair progressing well.

children.name: Text
children.value: Breaking news! Her Majesty the Queen seems to have vanished! No official statement has been released as yet, but Her Majesty's steward, Sir Archibald Blake, appeared frantic, when seen descending the palace steps this morning...

children.name: Text
children.value: An exhibition to show off the reclaimed Sceptre of Caponâ€” an heirloom said to run in the blood of Her Majesty and epitomize the triumph over La Corona at Trelawneyâ€” opened its grand doors earlier today. The queuing was endlessâ€” for not only were there denizens of Trelawney in attendance, but curious and patriotic visitors from all corners of the empire.

children.name: Text
children.value: After great service to both a city and a nation, [Participants Current Profile CompanyName] has been officially appointed Warden of Trelawney and Governor of Crown Falls at a grand ceremony conducted by Her Majesty The Queen, Empress Royal of The Southern Territories.

children.name: Text
children.value: Sail to the specified location with your salvager.

children.name: Text
children.value: Select your salvager and click on "Dive". Sit back and wait for your diving bell to return from the depths.

children.name: Text
children.value: Obtain an item with Echo-Location from Old Nate and activate it.

children.name: Text
children.value: Follow the signals from the echo-locator to find diving spots throughout the region.

children.name: Text
children.value: Look for the island that matches the map and dive where the X marks the spot.

children.name: Text
children.value: Old Nate can never get enough scrap for his projects, and would be delighted if you could give him any you find during your dives.

children.name: Text
children.value: Old Nate is after a specific bit of sunken machinery to help inspire his own designs. Be on the lookout during your divesâ€” he'll no doubt give you something for it.

children.name: Text
children.value: Old Nate wishes to conduct post-mortems on some of the more peculiar species of deep-dwelling sealife, in the knowledge that their many adaptations can inspire his own designs.

children.name: Text
children.value: Old Nate wants you to keep a lookout for any ancient technology on the seabed. This region was once a cradle of civilisation, and good ideas are timeless.

children.name: Text
children.value: Old Nate wants you to recover a sacred pirate talisman before the pirates do, lest it bring about their reunification and resurgence â€” either that or because it will sell for a lot of gold.

children.name: Text
children.value: A peculiar society believing themselves the descendents of Atlantis will do all they can to prevent your discovery of the city of their forefathers.

children.name: Text
children.value: Old Nate has acquired a treasure map from a dubious source. The marked co-ordinates will either lead you to riches, or else a whole world of trouble.

children.name: Text
children.value: Old Nate has found an area for you to scan with an echo sounder. One of his underlings claims to have seen and underwater city inhabited by nymphs there, believe it or not.

children.name: Text
children.value: Old Nate has found another promising spot for you to scan with the echo sounder. Up, up and away from the action as usual, he saw no reason to get involved until the fighting was over. While not unsympathetic towards the rebel cause, he sees no reason not to loot their ship now it is good and sunk.

children.name: Text
children.value: Mines surround a diving spot that Old Nate thinks very promising indeed, he just needs someone braveâ€” or foolishâ€” enough to go there for him.

children.name: Text
children.value: Old Nate has asked you to avoid some mines laid by unscrupulous looter-rival Scofield, who is trying to plunder a popular trade route. If there happen to be any victims already though, Old Nate sees no harm in picking through the bodies.

children.name: Text
children.value: The (very) elusive Scofield has been laying mines to snare unsuspecting ships again. Old Nate nobly urges you to do the right thing once more and destroy them.

children.name: Text
children.value: Old Nate wants you to bring him some soap, so that his employees can keep the automata in clean working order.

children.name: Text
children.value: Old Nate wants you to bury him in spectaclesâ€” providing him a stock of assorted lenses for his new inventions.

children.name: Text
children.value: Old Nate has asked you to deliver some materials in their purest form.

children.name: Text
children.value: Old Nate wants you to deliver some modern technology for him to examine and repurpose.

children.name: Text
children.value: Old Nate is missing that special something to bring one of his creations to life. He hopes you will have what he needs.

children.name: Text
children.value: Old Nate swears by fish oil as a daily supplement, and would like you to deliver some for him and his employeesâ€” there seems to be a silent accord that will do them all good.

children.name: Text
children.value: Old Nate is desperate for some caffeine to keep him ticking through the night as he works on his inventions. Sounds like his employees depend on it too.

children.name: Text
children.value: Old Nate wants you to photograph a production facility in order to see how modern factories make things.

children.name: Text
children.value: Old Nate is trying to recover some of the spoils of war even while the fighting still rages! Wary of being sucked in, he has asked for your protection.

children.name: Text
children.value: Old Nate is constructing a mechanical wonderâ€” a lifelike automaton designed to go about its business like a humanâ€” and he needs your help with the parts.

children.name: Text
children.value: Old Nate doesn't care for grand occasions, but the challenge of making elaborate fireworks is too tempting for him to resist. He wants you to bring him all he needs to get started.

children.name: Text
children.value: Any old scrap you find, just so you know, I'd be interested in. The grubbier and tattier the better.

children.name: Text
children.value: Paper company ship sank 'round here, perhaps you can help me sniff out a story? Maybe a gummed-up print press...

children.name: Text
children.value: Drill bits or bits of drillâ€” not fussedâ€”need 'em for me next bore. There must be some down there, what with all the quarrying along our coasts nowadays.

children.name: Text
children.value: As a self-sustaining bloke, I'd be overjoyed to see any smashed-up Hydroelectric Wheels you find, alright?

children.name: Text
children.value: Obsolete Machines can tell us a lotâ€” almost all the best ideas lie screwed up at the bottom of the paper bin.

children.name: Text
children.value: Best to learn from other people's mistakes, I say. There's no shortage of ship turbines down there, thanks to all them accidents that made way for the steamships we know today.

children.name: Text
children.value: We'll never surpass Mother Nature's powers of invention, I don't imagine. Not unless we start taking her weirdest creations apart, and stirring through their insides.

children.name: Text
children.value: Fascinating food filters they have, all them little planktons bouncing off the blades in their gobs. I can use that!

children.name: Text
children.value: Fascinating food filters they have, all them little planktons bouncing off the blades in their gobs. I'll use that!

children.name: Text
children.value: This one's not for science by the byâ€” it's for eating. I got a taste for it ballooning in the east. Now, which bit was the liver again...?

children.name: Text
children.value: This thing is nine-tenths water, imagine that! Boggles the mind it does, but as a matter-of-fact, I'm working on some organics myself...

children.name: Text
children.value: Ancient-looking thing eh? But that's a sign it's stood the test of time, like all the greatest inventions...

children.name: Text
children.value: I accumulate know-how the same way I accumulate junk. Down on the seabed lie all the little tidbits of wisdom left to us by our forefathersâ€” be a terrible shame not to cannibalise it, eh?

children.name: Text
children.value: The Pirates are desperate for that ring! Fend 'em off or the power of the old pirate kings will be restored, and piracy will rule the seas once more! Also, I won't be able to sell it.

children.name: Text
children.value: Oh gawd, get out yer tridents, its the Society of Atlanteans againâ€” if they reckon the ancient polis is down there, they'll stop at nothing to keep the entrance a secret.

children.name: Text
children.value: I've got this one treasure mapâ€” and it's not that I don't trust the rotten human that gave it meâ€” but we won't know if it's a trap 'til we dive. That's where you come in...

children.name: Text
children.value: I knew it! That map was as genuine as my back tooth. Here's your share of the spoils, me old bird.

children.name: Text
children.value: Sorry about that mix upâ€” win some, lose some. Don't let one dodgy tip-off dent your enthusiasm or next time you could be missing out!

children.name: Text
children.value: One of my...employees...swears they were 'napped by sea nymphs, and wined and dined in the sunken court of a coral queen. Far be it from me to disbelieveâ€” why not sound it out with that ocarina I gave yer?

children.name: Text
children.value: I took me seat up in the gods to watch Her Majesty drub another of her poor, oppressed colonies into submission. Anyway, I'm pretty sure I'm the only one to have noticed that tragic beaut go down with all its plunderâ€” find the echo, its down there somewhere!

children.name: Text
children.value: Since I'm a poor frail old man who never leaves his workshop, (ahem) I need a brave navigator to recover something precious to me. Alright I won't lie, there'll be mines everywhereâ€” place is a ruddy lobster trap. The cache down there though, corr!

children.name: Text
children.value: When villains like Scofield kill to deprive people of their possessions... I know I ain't so bad. He set mines on a major seawayâ€” think of all those lives! ...'course, anything wrecked already is fair game though, right?

children.name: Text
children.value: Scofield's up to his old tricks againâ€” fancy laying mines in a tranquil reef! You'll blow up those charges won't yer? My only concern is for the welfare of passing ships, see...

children.name: Text
children.value: Lovely, now I can gather all the loose sea sponge I needâ€” Eh? What Scofield? ...Oh right, 'course, yeahâ€” THAT Scofieldâ€” well, why didn't you say?! Ha! Showed him didn't we, eh? Hm.

children.name: Text
children.value: A bit of shine is dandy, but if the automata aren't kept clean, their mechanisms jam. They're a sorry sight when it happens. It's like they've lost all self-respect.

children.name: Text
children.value: There's nothing wrong with my beady eyesâ€” twenty-twenty vision, me! No, I wants glasses for the lensesâ€” for me telescopes and such.

children.name: Text
children.value: It's good to have some alloys...

children.name: Text
children.value: I'm running low on zinc, will you galvanise this old fella?

children.name: Text
children.value: I need top brass, perhaps you could blow yer bugle for some?

children.name: Text
children.value: I'm running out of quartz, got yer bucket and spade ready?

children.name: Text
children.value: Will you pass the salt, Peter? And will you pass the pepper, Paul? A-hahaha...

children.name: Text
children.value: I'm on the lookout for metals in particular...

children.name: Text
children.value: I'm all out of gold...I've rooted right to the very back of me mouth...

children.name: Text
children.value: I like tearing all the new stuff apart with me talons, and I'll even pay you to bring it me, how's about that!

children.name: Text
children.value: I'm missing a few last bits and bobs...

children.name: Text
children.value: It might be finished, but it's too ugly even for me...got any veneers to cover it up?

children.name: Text
children.value: Just a few tiny little wires stand between this little beauty and artificial intelligence!

children.name: Text
children.value: All it's missing is portholes...don't happen to have any glass do you?

children.name: Text
children.value: I've just had a last-minute ideaâ€” got any lightbulbs?

children.name: Text
children.value: A spoonful of oil a day stops me rusting upâ€” and all me employees; they're made in my image them machine-heads are!

children.name: Text
children.value: You can't expect to work all night without coffee to chew...and my employees practically run on the stuff!

children.name: Text
children.value: So how do you run them power plants of yours then?

children.name: Text
children.value: I'd like a few more assembly lines of my own, and was hoping for some inspiration...

children.name: Text
children.value: Clocks take a lot of fiddling about to understand they does, wouldn't hurt to save a bit of time, eh!

children.name: Text
children.value: If you're a scavenger, you can't always wait for the battle to die down, and yet I don't bloody-well want them thinking I'm taking part neither. What I'm trying to say isâ€” I need you as a human shield...hahaha

children.name: Text
children.value: I've dreams of sophistication. Not for meself you understand, but for me automataâ€”  still ain't nothing like humans, even after five-hundred-and-thirty-odd tries. Perhaps I could use your brains for nr. 531?

children.name: Text
children.value: Nahh, even with your help, the 531 ain't anywhere close to perfect. One for the scrapheapâ€” unless of course, you want it?

children.name: Text
children.value: Right, this time, a completely different line in automata. I find it's easier to get sense out of these bloody things if you put them in their place. Talking of which...Ha!...mind giving us a hand?

children.name: Text
children.value: After all that effort, this has to be one of the worstâ€” ruddy thing keeps combusting on me! If you want to take it off me hands I'm not going to stop you...

children.name: Text
children.value: I bloody swear, this is the last time before I go back to making cars and zeppelins like any sensible person. Reckon I've learned me lessons from the Mk.8â€” long live 9!

children.name: Text
children.value: I should have called it the IncinerN8, stupid ruddy thing! I mean it has its moments, I'll give it that, but I'm not risking all me other stuff for it. If you want it, take itâ€” I've lost me appetite for automata.

children.name: Text
children.value: Nothing gives me a thrill like messing around with gunpowder!

children.name: Text
children.value: Right these ones are going to be even more spectacular...

children.name: Text
children.value: And people say I'm anti-social! I'm about to provide something to warm the hearts of all them folks at Archie's next royal display! I promise it's no plotâ€” I'm not that kind of guy.

children.name: Text
children.value: The scrappiest possible kind of scrap.

children.name: Text
children.value: You can already see these rare metals glistening in Old Nate's widening eyes.

children.name: Text
children.value: In the honour of the brilliant inventor, Nathaniel Spoondr- wait, did the eyes just move...?

children.name: Text
children.value: The artist's intention was to encapsulate the spirit of the industrial revolution, its technological advancements and the labour movement.

children.name: Text
children.value: Follow the Queen to Cape Trelawney; a new session with an immense continental island. Remarkable treasures are said to be buried in these watersâ€” the remnants of a great sea battle. You're going to need a diving bell to get themâ€” the newest invention of Old Nate, a nearby drifter. He'll also help turn any rubbish you find into inventions to fuel the growth of your territorial capital!

children.name: Text
children.value: Explore the story of the Battle of Trelawney, and meet two new characters: Old Nate and Vasco Oliveira.

children.name: Text
children.value: Explore and settle in a new session, with multiple islands and one vast continental island.

children.name: Text
children.value: Use your new diving bell to recover shiny sunken treasures.

children.name: Text
children.value: Craft inventive new items at Old Nate's island with scrap you find.

children.name: Text
children.value: Free some space in your ship's cargo to load the invention. You can throw away goods by right-clicking on them.

children.name: Text
children.value: Oh yes...King JoÃ£o will be gratified.

children.name: Text
children.value: We are but servants to our respective mastersâ€¦

children.name: Text
children.value: I am Vasco Oliveira. I conduct the solemn and discreet business of none other than King JoÃ£o of A Coroa â€” that's La Corona to the plebs.

children.name: Text
children.value: You have likely met my tedious cousin Vicente...

children.name: Text
children.value: You can't imagine I wish to stay here at Trelawney, site of the most mortifying defeat in my proud nation's history, out of choice?

children.name: Text
children.value: We are here on short business, and then we shall be out of your way.

children.name: Text
children.value: Oh you've nothing to fear from us, we're not cousin Vicente's thuggish band.

children.name: Text
children.value: Vicente's mother thinks he's too embarassed to come for a family dinner; I daresay I would be too.

children.name: Text
children.value: I hope the thought of working with A Coroa doesn't disgust you so much to turn my offer down?

children.name: Text
children.value: The battle of Trelawney is far behind our two nation empires, is it time we compromised?

children.name: Text
children.value: I suppose I had better thank you.

children.name: Text
children.value: Ah! Old scars must run deep.

children.name: Text
children.value: You think that's bad, I saw Vicente lose an empire in just under a half hour.

children.name: Text
children.value: King JoÃ£o is not a patient man, and I have had to work so very hard for this thankless positionâ€¦

children.name: Text
children.value: We're only as good as our lastâ€¦

children.name: Text
children.value: Ah! Can I hope it's what we have been waiting for?

children.name: Text
children.value: Why, pray, are you so keen to do us a favour?

children.name: Text
children.value: We all have to choose a side sometimeâ€¦

children.name: Text
children.value: Oh, just passing through. These are neutral waters, are they not?

children.name: Text
children.value: I am under no obligation to explain the outrageously expensive apparatus we happen to have aboard.

children.name: Text
children.value: We have come only to pay our respects beside the grave of a once-great empire.

children.name: Text
children.value: Strange to see our mighty armada in bits, teeming with barnacles and limpets.

children.name: Text
children.value: In the years since Vicente's historic failure, our empire has been in steady decline...

children.name: Text
children.value: Vicente was very green, they should never given him commandâ€¦

children.name: Text
children.value: Domination and conquest. That is how A Coroa became knownâ€” and look where it got us.

children.name: Text
children.value: This land was once the pride of A Coroa; King JoÃ£o's summer retreat, and the proposed location of...well never mind thatâ€¦

children.name: Text
children.value: Let you build there, did she? A modern ruler, your Queen, I wouldn't have minded working for her.

children.name: Text
children.value: It's no great secret then, we are both looking for the Holy Sceptre of Capon...among other things.

children.name: Text
children.value: If we both delve into the haycock for that very special needle, there's more chance at least one of us snags a bloody thumb.

children.name: Text
children.value: We may be in a footrace, but there's no need for us to be in each others' way.

children.name: Text
children.value: The Holy Sceptre of Capon is irreplaceable. Centuries it presided, in the hands of our rulers, the instrument of our glory.

children.name: Text
children.value: Vicente thought it clever to split our national treasure, and the sceptre, across three different ships. But with the sceptre dismantled, belief evaporated.

children.name: Text
children.value: Though it was originally forged in three separate parts, only a harebrain like Vicente would have the audacity to dismantle it.

children.name: Text
children.value: The armada had never lost at sea while the sceptre was present, but Vicente had to overthink it didn't he?

children.name: Text
children.value: Vicente was supposed to move our national treasure to a secret vault. What could be more secret than the bottom of the sea!?

children.name: Text
children.value: The bird atop is a proud eagle, what else can it possibly be!? It's the timeless talisman of empire!

children.name: Text
children.value: Obviously, all of the lost treasure is of the greatest value, but King JoÃ£o has convinced himself the sceptre has the symbolic clout to save our fading empireâ€¦

children.name: Text
children.value: We lost so much treasure, it is easy to become distracted from the main prizeâ€¦

children.name: Text
children.value: Oh, so Old Nate let it slip he has been unfaithful? Dirty little man.

children.name: Text
children.value: We do not, as that oleaginous stinkerer does, refer to the holy staff of capon, as a "chicken stick".

children.name: Text
children.value: Your Queen will no doubt claim the Sceptre of Capon runs in the blood of both our royal lines. A claim you can rest assured, is entirely false.

children.name: Text
children.value: JoÃ£o has been an utterly incompetent King, but nothing compared to your Queen's father.

children.name: Text
children.value: Your Queen certainly seems to have inherited her mother's genes.

children.name: Text
children.value: I can't tell you how expensive all this diving apparatus was, and so far it has proved more than useless.

children.name: Text
children.value: We were only to stop here briefly, but now it seems we will be stuck here the entire summer.

children.name: Text
children.value: When are we going to dredge up something meaningful, I wonder?

children.name: Text
children.value: Oh dear, I seem to have found some of the sceptre! But how will you piece it together now?

children.name: Text
children.value: If King JoÃ£o can't have his sceptre, neither can your Queen.

children.name: Text
children.value: I can only apologise, it seems our two sides are destined to be at odds.

children.name: Text
children.value: You must know, the last thing I want is a repeat of the battle of Trelawney.

children.name: Text
children.value: I'd prefer for us not to be at each other's throats like thisâ€¦

children.name: Text
children.value: We have circumnavigated each other too long, it is time we went head-to-head.

children.name: Text
children.value: Ever feel you know exactly what is going to happen, but utterly powerless to stop it?

children.name: Text
children.value: Oh, keep the wretched bird! This is the second time my family have been humiliated here, cursed place! I must return to face my fate at the hands of King JoÃ£o. None of your pity thank you, it has been a long time coming.

children.name: Text
children.value: You gave it to that filthy mechanical bluebottle? The blasphemy! History's greatest treasure, now in the oily hands of one who calls it a "chicken stick"!

children.name: Text
children.value: I'm perplexed and astonished by your kindness. The sceptre may not save A Coroa, but thanks to you, it may very well save me. I hope your Queen is more forgiving of you than her father would have beenâ€¦

children.name: Text
children.value: I am not here to escape domestic dissatisfaction, but to address it. Our nation has lost its pride! But pride can be restored! This place, Trelawney, is the site of my father's great naval victory over our rivals La Corona.

children.name: Text
children.value: La Corona wanted to move their national treasures while they could, but the fleet caught them in the act.

children.name: Text
children.value: I am curious as to how father was able to relay his instructions so quickly from such a distance.

children.name: Text
children.value: The child that was me played out the battle of Trelawney countless times in the parlour on a miniature campaign table.

children.name: Text
children.value: Father's command from up on the cliff, that's what won us the day, not the actions of the much-trumpeted Admiral Nadasky.

children.name: Text
children.value: We were the victors here at Trelawney, yet all the spoils remain in the lap of Poseidon.

children.name: Text
children.value: He may have been on the winning side, but father always said Admiral Nadasky's carelessness had meant the Sceptre being lost to the waves.

children.name: Text
children.value: It was father's great regret he was never able to hold the Sceptre. I'm sure that insecurity about his position made him cling to power all the more perfervidly.

children.name: Text
children.value: The Sceptre of Capon has long granted its bearers indisputable authority. But it sank to the depths with La Corona's fleet.

children.name: Text
children.value: We share a bloodline you know. I have as much right to the sceptre as King JoÃ£o of La Corona.

children.name: Text
children.value: As this could easily be my last unofficial visit anywhere, I intend to enjoy my freedom.

children.name: Text
children.value: I had rather a stuffy childhood. So being out here, free and incognito, has one feeling pretty giddy.

children.name: Text
children.value: Ever been on a treasure hunt? Mother let me out in the garden on sunny days.

children.name: Text
children.value: Dear old Archie has been like a father to me, but had I told him I was coming here, he'd have sent for too many flowers and servants.

children.name: Text
children.value: Finding the sunken Sceptre of Caponâ€” the trophy we never claimed for that victoryâ€” can remind us of our past glories and restore the people's faith in their monarch.

children.name: Text
children.value: It's obvious why they're here. It's the same reason we're here; for the emblematic power that sceptre will give whoever owns it.

children.name: Text
children.value: One imagined if one was secretive enough, La Corona might not discover one's intentions, yet of course here they are, at the double.

children.name: Text
children.value: I saw it from the deck: an impish little man dredging up bits and pieces. He may be exactly what we requireâ€¦

children.name: Text
children.value: If we are to find anything in this graveyard, we might as well commission the vulture.

children.name: Text
children.value: I will happily shake those greasy paws if it means I get my sceptre.

children.name: Text
children.value: But we can't afford a war with La Corona, feeble though they may be, so I'm afraid you'll have to rely on your wits to beat this Oliveira to it.

children.name: Text
children.value: Could this beâ€¦? This is the journal of my father's strategist, the overrated Nadasky!

children.name: Text
children.value: Help me build it, and find the sceptre, and I shall designate you Warden of Trelawney, my official representative in these waters.

children.name: Text
children.value: I see we are not the first to pay Old Nate for these coordinates... I only hope we are the first to find what's down there.

children.name: Text
children.value: We shall build a new capital of the realm here, perhaps call it Crown Falls, in view of the sparkling cataracts you see the island posesses. This may be my greatest legacy.

children.name: Text
children.value: Admiral Nadasky writes that he defied the orders of my father! That treasonous Jack Tar, father should have had his head!

children.name: Text
children.value: This waterlogged log is in a terrible state, did you not bring any art restorers with you?

children.name: Text
children.value: When the exhibition is over, do remember to give it to my busbies, so I can toss it in with the rest of the bling.

children.name: Text
children.value: Now, if it were the centrepiece of a grand exhibition, the people in these parts will be reminded of how far-reaching is the influence of an Empress.

children.name: Text
children.value: My mother had a great deal of trouble saying the words "ocean bottom" but I find I have no difficulty at all!

children.name: Text
children.value: What a remarkable innovation! Can I have a go?

children.name: Text
children.value: The empire needs these potterers, those willing to try new things.

children.name: Text
children.value: He's with us, one hopes? Or is he the peculiar sort who doesn't take sides?

children.name: Text
children.value: Isn't he the spit of those chaps in the beggar's opera? We do so much want to like the poor.

children.name: Text
children.value: Some of father's orders were utterly bafflingâ€¦

children.name: Text
children.value: Father should have trusted those with naval expertiseâ€¦I mean it's now quite obvious he had little of that expertise himself.

children.name: Text
children.value: I always believed my father, when he claimed to be the unsung mastermind at the battle of Trelawney, but instead it was Nadasky all along saving his blushes.

children.name: Text
children.value: I may have been wrong about Admiral Nadasky. Upon my return to the capital, I shall have a great big pillar built in his honour.

children.name: Text
children.value: The facts here are plain. Had they followed only father's orders, La Corona would have won.

children.name: Text
children.value: The King my father draws further away from his daughter with each new revelation of Nadasky's log.

children.name: Text
children.value: This log is proof Nadasky may at least have had good intentions in his defiance of father's orders.

children.name: Text
children.value: This entry shows they persisted in deviating from Father's instructionsâ€¦

children.name: Text
children.value: Another part of Admiral Nadasky's logbookâ€¦fascinating readingâ€¦

children.name: Text
children.value: One is no dunce-hatted imbecile, but I rather think we'll need a class swot or two to decipher this; a university with a budding college of palaeographers to decipher Nadasky's shameful handwriting.

children.name: Text
children.value: Oh it's all much clearer now, do thank your expert bods at the University for all their brio.

children.name: Text
children.value: So you're playing best of three? I hope you realise the seriousness of such a gambleâ€” it seems you had better win.

children.name: Text
children.value: If you had the guts to bet my sceptre, you better get to it firstâ€¦

children.name: Text
children.value: What? We know the spot now. Or do you need a ducking?

children.name: Text
children.value: It must be around here somewhere. Proceed with your goobling, or however you call it.

children.name: Text
children.value: We're groping in the dark here! How does the carrion bird know where to plunge?

children.name: Text
children.value: This is one of the locations Nadasky mentioned in the journal. Prepare your diving bell!

children.name: Text
children.value: What Nadasky writes of hereâ€¦ The heroes that tilted the battle in our favour were stranded! They never returned, but we may still learn what became of them.

children.name: Text
children.value: A mere frigate against a ship-of-the-line...? Only Father's obsession with the sceptre can  have clouded his judgement so! The last piece must be down there in the murk.

children.name: Text
children.value: Nadasky sketched the SantÃ­ssima VitÃ³ria in his journal before it wrecked on the western coast.

children.name: Text
children.value: Still, his detailed observations of the battle are priceless...we must investigate the locations he describes.

children.name: Text
children.value: Don't you think this place resembles Nadasky's description?

children.name: Text
children.value: According to the journal, this is where all those ships sank...

children.name: Text
children.value: We found it! But wait â€” where is the grand Eagle at its top? This is but a portion of the rod!

children.name: Text
children.value: The Sceptre is worthless if it is not whole.

children.name: Text
children.value: Why did their Admiral Silva think it prudent to break up a lucky sceptre?

children.name: Text
children.value: Let us see if you have the prowess of an Admiral Nadaskyâ€¦

children.name: Text
children.value: A part of me would be excited to see the battle of Trelawney recreated!

children.name: Text
children.value: This Oliveira reeks of defeat, you just have to tip the scales!

children.name: Text
children.value: I dreamed of seeing such a battle at Trelawney each night as a child!

children.name: Text
children.value: Marvellous! You know, seeing it, it really doesn't look much like an eagle does it? Oh well, none of my subjects will ever dare question it!

children.name: Text
children.value: My gratitude is heartfelt.  This is a new emblem of state behind which my subjects will surely rally!

children.name: Text
children.value: I hear it has been stolen from the exhibition?! Crime is becoming a terrible problem for the Empire. I will find that sceptre, but for now I'm sorry your efforts have gone in vain.

children.name: Text
children.value: So the Sceptre of Capon has somehow made it into the hands of La Corona? Well-played â€¦but It jolly billy better not have been you responsible!

children.name: Text
children.value: But, in the end, I care less for the sceptre, more for the Nadasky's revelations concerning my father.

children.name: Text
children.value: The father I sawâ€” the great tacticianâ€” appears never to have existed; and yet a daughter's love prevails through the absurdity of his weakness.

children.name: Text
children.value: Yes! Oh, for a second I thought he'd beat us to it!

children.name: Text
children.value: Now it's time for Vasco to hold up his end of the bargain.

children.name: Text
children.value: We have the Eagle! And Vasco promised to yield the pommel, he promised!

children.name: Text
children.value: We have the pieces, now it's time to puzzle it together.

children.name: Text
children.value: I have not undergone all this trouble so that flea may lay his oily digits on it!

children.name: Text
children.value: Like I will leave my scepter with him all unsupervisedâ€¦

children.name: Text
children.value: Haven't we plenty of scholars versed in the art of restoration already?

children.name: Text
children.value: There's no use owning such a treasure, unless it can be grandly displayed for my subjects. They shall see that in ambition, I am at least my father's equal.

children.name: Text
children.value: The most precious of cherries to top the cake!

children.name: Text
children.value: Mr. Oliveira was truly a man of his word. Had it been me, I'd never have let him have our piece of the sceptre.

children.name: Text
children.value: In particular I am indebted to you for helping me see the king my father as he really wasâ€” warts and all.

children.name: Text
children.value: Well it's high time I returned to rescue poor old Archie - he may otherwise start chattering about his bowels. Look after Crown Falls for me, won't you? I only really care for the taxes.

children.name: Text
children.value: There is no mistaking it; this was once La Corona's great flagship. The eagle must be here.

children.name: Text
children.value: A humble outpost now, perhaps. But it promises to become the largest capital of my empire!

children.name: Text
children.value: I see the new settlement is progressing well, the empire needs to develop a lasting presence here in the south.

children.name: Text
children.value: I can see it â€”a brilliant metropolis rising here, from the memory of the victory my father masterminded. A shining new jewel in the crown of my empire.

children.name: Text
children.value: The warm southern air makes me feel strong and well. Purposeful, you might say.

children.name: Text
children.value: I can still smell father's victory here at Trelawney, it is his greatest legacy.

children.name: Text
children.value: It is far from being the capital I envisioned, there is much to do!

children.name: Text
children.value: Once my capital is all set, Archie will let me return to these sunny shores anytime I like!

children.name: Text
children.value: My dreamsâ€” one's youthful imaginings of this place of triumphâ€” so dutifully have you made whole.

children.name: Text
children.value: This is it: my metropolis, standing tall and proudâ€” forever a symbol of my greatness.

children.name: Text
children.value: If this is to become a radiant metropolis, we need to make some additionsâ€¦

children.name: Text
children.value: How can these people go without this!? I know I absolutely could notâ€¦

children.name: Text
children.value: The magic of the crown: I ask for it, and it appears!

children.name: Text
children.value: This city is now closer to magnificence!

children.name: Text
children.value: I only have one last vision: a World's Fair sitting atop this magnificent metropolis!

children.name: Text
children.value: It will not be an imperial capital until the World's Fair is complete.

children.name: Text
children.value: The World's Fair! This may very well be the finest city in the whole of my empire!

children.name: Text
children.value: People will come from far and wide to behold the Sceptre of Capon â€” the ultimate exponent of my authority as a ruler.

children.name: Text
children.value: Welcome to Trelawney, graveyard to thousands; the gift that keeps on giving, hehe.

children.name: Text
children.value: Trelawney, site of one of the great naval battles, now a veritable trove of lost treasure.

children.name: Text
children.value: Plunder to be got if you sink down deep enough. I may be able to help you along a tad with that.

children.name: Text
children.value: A lot of meat and cartilage left on the bones of these ships, especially on their underbellies.

children.name: Text
children.value: Don't bother about what he's up to. Just you concentrate on your own digging.

children.name: Text
children.value: This Vasco looks stiffer than week-old bat kabobâ€” on his last legs, like. No match for someone like you.

children.name: Text
children.value: Work with Oliveira, who said that? hehe. No, no, I'm all yours!

children.name: Text
children.value: Yaps a lot about his cousin, I find. Easy to boot a man while he's down, eh?

children.name: Text
children.value: Even after all this time, you still see the odd eyeball surface, belched up from that tomb of a trench below.

children.name: Text
children.value: Terrible, war, ain't it? Well, for the luckless beggars who had to fight in itâ€¦hahahaa

children.name: Text
children.value: Sometimes you'll see a skull on the seabed, watchin' you like. I just smile back.

children.name: Text
children.value: If you're waiting for them dead sailors to give you permission, you'll be waiting a long time, hahahaha!

children.name: Text
children.value: Don't plan on fixing yourself there too long, this place is like a thoroughfare for conqueror-types.

children.name: Text
children.value: Your peninsula might be under the Queenie's umbrella for now, but I know from experience, nothing ever lasts.

children.name: Text
children.value: If you don't pick a side, you can't be on the wrong one.

children.name: Text
children.value: While the big boys and girls are duking it out, the likes of you and I can sneak stuff away while they ain't looking.

children.name: Text
children.value: Of course, my expertise costs a pretty penny, hehe.

children.name: Text
children.value: What your Queenie wants is a diving bell. I couldâ€¦ lease you my prototype.

children.name: Text
children.value: Tired of coming back up with nothing but scrap?

children.name: Text
children.value: Tired of coming back up with nothing but scrap? I can point you to the good stuff, for a reasonable fee...

children.name: Text
children.value: Do you think I got this far by throwing stuff away? Bring that rubbish to me, I'll polish it up.

children.name: Text
children.value: Not half bad, eh? I can turn around your junk, so long as I get to keep the odd smidge of gimcrackery.

children.name: Text
children.value: Alright, you got me. I been helping Vasco. Don't take offence old mucker, common sense to back both horses.

children.name: Text
children.value: How's about I do you a special favourâ€”just for you mindâ€” to make up for my heinous betrayal of trustâ€¦

children.name: Text
children.value: I'm more interested in all the other sweet collector's items down there.

children.name: Text
children.value: All so hung up on that chicken-on-a-stick, what about all the rest of the Trewlaney hoard?

children.name: Text
children.value: Forget all that old flannel about her father, old Queenie's in it for the loot just as much as we are.

children.name: Text
children.value: Don't forget that Admiral Nadasky disobeyed his King and it all paid off.

children.name: Text
children.value: Being a prototype, I will ask you sign a waiver for yer life before you use it.

children.name: Text
children.value: Without the metal suit you're vulnerable as a homeless hermit crab.

children.name: Text
children.value: The Trelawney hoard's a diversion, everyone's forgotten all the older, more valuable finds.

children.name: Text
children.value: I have a personal asphyxiation with underwater treasure.

children.name: Text
children.value: Watch out for the octopuses, they like to keep all the good stuff under wraps.

children.name: Text
children.value: The diving bell gives those sharks something to chew on at least.

children.name: Text
children.value: See anything shiny down there then?

children.name: Text
children.value: Any mermaid's open their purses of pearls for yer then?

children.name: Text
children.value: Never be too sure all the life has gone out of something.

children.name: Text
children.value: It'd cost you an arm and a leg to buy that new.

children.name: Text
children.value: Looks like it was made to be split into three. Shouldn't be too hard to put back together...

children.name: Text
children.value: There you have it! One reconstituted chicken stick, good as new.

children.name: Text
children.value: The maiden descent for me beautiful diving bell! I've got all seven of me fingers crossed for you, you little ocean-going guinea pig, you.

children.name: Text
children.value: Botched the dive did ya? Glass get all misted up or something?

children.name: Text
children.value: Hopefully the water won't gush in like the only other time I tested it. Well, good luck!

children.name: Text
children.value: Either you've got the bends, or you've come back disappointed.

children.name: Text
children.value: Corr, that'll fetch a few clamsâ€¦

children.name: Text
children.value: Now here's something; a proper pressure gauge. You'll be able to go to much deeper and darker places nowâ€¦

children.name: Text
children.value: This balloon is a rather special innovation of mine, gives you a much better view of them hidden reefs!

children.name: Text
children.value: Now this is arguably my greatest invention to date. Like invisible hands reaching through the air, andâ€¦there! That sound will keep you true.

children.name: Text
children.value: I can put something together for you, but Oliveira dropped by a while ago asking for the same thing and I'm all out of garbage.

children.name: Text
children.value: He is quite clever that Vasco, I'll give him that.

children.name: Text
children.value: Maybe I'll wait until you two finish each other off before diving in.

children.name: Text
children.value: Another battle of Trelawney? Oh goody!

children.name: Text
children.value: There you go! I told you I'd give you special treatment.

children.name: Text
children.value: There! Never say I don't care about youâ€” even if it is true.

children.name: Text
children.value: The spaniel fetches the Queen her stick then, eh? Well, a man like me can't afford to be loyal.

children.name: Text
children.value: It'd be funnier if you gave the three of us one bit eachâ€¦

children.name: Text
children.value: Give me the sceptre? Corr, I'm honoured! And rich! Haha, good on yer, my absolute gamble on you has paid off.

children.name: Text
children.value: You do realise I am just going to sell this sceptre to the highest bidder? So no moral victory for you, if that's what you thought it was.

children.name: Text
children.value: Gave it back to La Corona, 'cos it was theirs to begin with? Whatever happened to finders keepers?

children.name: Text
children.value: Maybe that miserable geezer Vasco will be happy now. Or maybe not. That's how it is with miserable geezers.

children.name: Text
children.value: Exhibition royalties? Blimey, you're really milking that chicken stick for all its got, ain't yer?

children.name: Text
children.value: I swear something funny's going on down there!

children.name: Text
children.value: Something's amiss with your diving bell.

children.name: Text
children.value: If anything's happened, I'm not liable.
